  "description" : "At the end of the Ming Dynasty, Japanese pirates roamed the coastal areas of Jiangnan. Jiang Lingyun, father of Jiang Liuer, was secretly dispatched by the imperial court to investigate the piracy. Jiang Liuer was temporarily fostered at Lingyun Temple. There, he simultaneously played Go against three young monks and won decisively. The old monk, Yuande, deeply admired Jiang Liuer`s unparalleled Go prodigy.\nThe anti-piracy hero, Yaodao Wang, was suspected of colluding with the pirates. During his investigation, Jiang Lingyun was killed by an arrow shot by one of Prince Fu`s men. Jiang Liuer resolved to learn martial arts from Yaodao Wang to avenge his father. Yaodao Wang told him that he lacked talent in martial arts and should instead pursue the path of Go. He explained that if he could become a Go master, he could be with the emperor, thus exposing Prince Fu`s conspiracy and avenging his father.\nOn Master Yuande`s advice, Jiang Liuer ventured out to learn various Go styles and participate in the once-every-twenty-years National Go Championship. However, Jiang Liuer mistakenly became the disciple of Jin Weiyuan, the \"Quick Axe Hand\" of the Xijin Chess Academy. Jin Weiyuan was unscrupulous and often took Jiang Liuer to gamble on chess, telling him that to win, one must \"use any means necessary.\" In a game against the veteran chess player Liu Nanru, Jiang Liuer used the method of \"long thinking\" to wear down the old master and ultimately lose his life, causing great controversy. Later, Jiang Liuer felt very guilty about this.\nsource: bgm.tv\\googletranslate",
